50|$|The Varsity was {{introduced}} to replace the Wellington T10 trainer. Following deliveries to trials units the first production aircraft were delivered for operational use in 1951 to No. 201 Advanced Flying School at RAF Swinderby, where {{they were used to}} train pilots to fly multi-engined aircraft. It also equipped two Air Navigator Schools in 1952, and the Bomber Command Bombing school, with the job <b>of</b> <b>training</b> <b>crews</b> for RAF Bomber-Command's V-bomber crews.|$|R
50|$|The driver {{suffered}} major {{injury to}} his arms, {{as a result}} of the screw reversing lever whipping around when he released it. The accident brought to light the importance <b>of</b> <b>train</b> <b>crews</b> being <b>trained</b> on the specific locomotives they were driving, rather than simply a common general instruction on steam locomotives. Neither the driver or fireman had ever worked 60532 before, and were unaware of the locomotive's sensitivity to priming, which led to the accident.|$|R
